News - Date: 01 July 2017Written by: Kaizer Nengovhela / Viewed: 36Mr Lutendo Ramahala (28) of Vhumatshelo Crop Farming at Tshikhwani was recognised as the best young farmer during the National Youth in Agriculture Fisheries and Forestry&nbsp;competition held at the Kieviets Kroon Country Estate in Pretoria last Friday.Ramahala won the smallholder category and received R50 000 and a certificate.During the event, the Deputy Minister of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries,&nbsp;Bheki Cele, said that his department wanted&nbsp;to assist young people, particularly those from previously disadvantaged rural areas, in their farming endeavours.According to him, emerging farmers are playing an important role in food production. He encouraged&nbsp;young people to become involved by starting gardens at the back of their houses. &quot;We appreciate and value the contribution of young people in economic activities of the province,&quot; said Cele.Ramahala farms with spinach and tomatoes and sells these to a big supermarket and to members of the community. He currently employs five people.Young farmer&nbsp;Mr Lutendo Rahamala (left) photographed with&nbsp;his award. With him in the photo are Chief Mbulaheni Ramabulana and Mr Tshifhiwa Mukondeleli.Kaizer Nengovhela started writing stories for Limpopo Mirror more than a decade ago, in 2 000. Prior to that he had a five year stint at Phala-Phala FM as sports presenter. In 2005 Kaizer received an award from the province&#39;s premier as Best Sports Presenter. The same year he was also nominated as Best Sports Reporter by the Makhado Municipality. Kaizer was awarded the Mathatha Tsedu award in 2014.Email: kaizerdo@webmail.co.za